segments.text: My name is Phillip S. Smith.
I go by Phil.
I have initially joined Mitchell Energy and Development Corp., which is the parent company of the Woodlands Corporation, in January of 1980.
Prior to that time, I was a partner with Arthur Anderson & Co. here in Houston, Texas.
I initially joined Mitchell as the Senior Vice President, Chief Financial Officer, and reported to Joe Williams, who was President of the Administration and Finance Division at the time.
Subsequent to Joe Williams leaving, I assumed the position of the President of the Administration and Financial Division.

of Mitchell Energy and Development Corp., which basically encompasses all of the non-operating aspects of the Mitchell companies, such as finance, accounting, administration, data processing, public relations, anything not directly related to operations.
Do you have the legal office as well?
Pardon?
The legal office, you had that as well?
Legal, yes, legal would fall in that category.
Since that time, that was, I forget exactly when Joe Williams left, but probably 81 or so, I would imagine, 1981, I guess, perhaps late 1980.

As a result of those functions, all of those functions to the extent they're provided across the board to the entire Mitchell Energy and Development Corporation, which includes the energy operations as well as the real estate operations.

My involvement in the real estate aspects has been primarily from, say, the administration accounting finance standpoint, and I've been closely involved in financing the Woodlands operations since joining Mitchell.
Tell me a little bit more about your background.
Do you have degrees from
Yes, I graduated with a BS degree from Mississippi State University in 1957.
I have a CPA.
Joined Arthur Anderson and Co. on graduation from Mississippi State.
Worked one year, went in the U.S. Army Artillery for two years as a second lieutenant.
Rejoined Arthur Anderson.
in May of 1960 and was with them here in the Houston office until I joined Mitchell in January of 1980.
At the time I left Mitchell, I was a partner in the firm.
You mean Anderson?
I left Arthur Anderson & Co.
I was a partner in the firm and had responsibility for the firm's oil and gas industry competence program.
How did Mitchell find out about you?
Where did you two link up?
Previous to joining Mitchell, I had been the engagement partner on the Mitchell audit for a number of years and had rotated off of the audit.
And in connection with the staff reorganization that they were undertaking in late 79 and early 80, I joined the company in, say, January of 1980.
and in effect took over most of the responsibilities that Bill Tonary had previously held as Chief Financial Officer at that time.
How, on a work-a-day basis, would you interact with the Woodlands Corporation?
Generally speaking, well, as I said, in all of the areas that I have responsibility for,
accounting, finance, probably the major ones, personnel, all of those different areas.
A number of people that work for me in those areas are more, you know, are directly involved on a day-to-day basis.
My primary involvement or greatest personal involvement would probably tend to be in the finance and accounting areas.
What kind of expertise are you bringing to that that is required?
Well, of course, any just the normal, you know, we have responsibility.

My area, you know, has responsibility for all the reporting requirements, financial reporting requirements for Mitchell Energy and Development Corp., which is a public company, and so we keep all of the accounting records and prepare the financial statements and everything.
And the data processing?
All of the Mitchell entities, and that's, would all come under my supervision and responsibility, and the same thing with the financing.
you know, the various different loans and financial structures that are required to finance the entire company's operations, including real estate, would come under my area of responsibility.
During the, you know, the 80s, Houston went through a rather severe economic downturn.
How did that affect your job and the Woodlands particularly?
Because it did affect
Yes, well of course initially when I joined Mitchell in January 1980, Houston was still booming.
We had one or two very good years after that in terms of profitability and earnings.
And then starting I think in either 81 or 82, you know, earnings began to decline because of the
decline in oil prices or the erosion of the oil economy, which caused the banks to have problems, which caused the real estate industry in Houston to have problems.
And probably the, in 1986 when the price of oil really went down I think as low as $10 a barrel, was when it really began to strongly impact
not only the energy operations of Mitchell Energy and Development Corp, but also obviously the real estate operations.
And the company went through a period of very low earnings, about $8 million a year for a couple of years there, fiscal 87 or 88, I believe.
And since then, you know, we've started to come back in terms of earnings perspective.

But during that time, particularly starting in, say, in 86, fiscal 86 or fiscal 87, you know, a company had to make a number of adjustments from an operating and financial standpoint in terms of cutting back on cost, overhead, employee head counts, and everything.
in order to adapt to a different operating environment that existed during that period of time.
I've been told that the woodlands is self-sufficient.
Has that always been true?
Self-sufficient?
Financially, that it earns a profit.
Generally speaking, they've been profitable.

Because of the nature, though, of the company, the Woodlands Corporation's assets, which a substantial portion of which is undeveloped land, and the fact that they have a relatively high level of debt on the real estate side, a lot of the financial debt is guaranteed by the parent corporation, which
is what enables the real estate operation to carry its financial, you know, or support its MND that it has.
So, because the picture we've been getting is that the Woodlands is part of George Mitchell's vision.
It doesn't seem
necessarily be something he's doing because of the immediate return he's going to get.
It's rather, well, some people have poppy farms.
George Mitchell's building the woodlands.
Has that been your impression as well?
Well, of course, hopefully it'll ultimately turn out to be an economic
success.

Generally speaking, I would say George and most people perceive that the energy, speaking in terms of today's time, 1990, late 1990, you know, I think the energy portion of the company is looking for the near and mid-term is more likely to have a major impact on the company's overall operations, whereas
you probably won't see any significant benefits from the real estate operations in terms of level of earnings and cash flows and things of that nature.
It would be more a mid to long term time frame, which would say being anywhere from five to 15 years from today's time.
The nature of a
long master plan community like the Woodlands.
You have a lot of front end costs and a lot of major investments to make and a lot of carrying costs in terms of interest charges, property taxes, things of that nature.
And so as a result, generally speaking, real estate has been a net borrower of funds in the 1980s.
Is that just the Woodlands, or are you including the thing at Snowmass and Pirate World?
I tend to speak, when I speak the Woodlands Corporation, that would be, it's all in effect in one corporation, although they have a number of different subsidiaries.
I'm basically referring to real estate in total, although the Woodlands itself probably comprises two-thirds or three-fourths of the real estate operations.
So it's by far the...
It's the most significant part of the overall real estate operation.
But we haven't precisely separated out the operations of the woodlands itself in the head of real estate operations.
I suppose it could be done, but we don't necessarily report our financial statements on that basis.
As we've interviewed these other gentlemen,
Every corporation has a culture to it, an environment that is unique to that corporation.
It seems that an essential element, which wasn't surprising, but the strength of it is a little surprising.
of Mitchell Edgerton Development Corporation, Woodlands Corporation, the personality of George Mitchell, his vision, his sense of what he wants to do.
How have you perceived George Mitchell's influence in the development of the Woodlands?
I mean, obviously he was the one who set the vision in motion, but he's also done many, many other things ancillary to the original vision, which to some many were a little bit surprising.
Well, I think clearly, you know, George Mitchell has his very definite views on
what the woodland should be, how it should be developed, and what the components of it would be.
And while he does delegate a lot of the day-to-day operations, I mean, clearly he's got pretty much a hands-on approach in terms of the direction, overall management, major decisions that go into the
The overall development of the woodlands, as to the type of development, the character of it, things of that nature.
That's clearly the case.
You know, things such as Hart, who's been in the Advanced Research Center, Cynthia Woods Mitchell-Povig, things of that nature.
And so it's happening, yeah.
And I was intrigued by the Venture Capital Group, which, so folklore goes, was started in a lobby, you know.
You grabbed somebody and gave them $15 million and said, do it.
And it spun off into something.
Well, I don't know if it was quite that simple.
Well, I've been told that story by a couple of people who maybe were repeating the same source.
I don't know.
Yeah.
Well, I think it actually probably evolved a little bit more over time.
You know, part of the concept was to try to bring startup companies to the world.
And nurture tech.
Yeah.
High tech type of medical type areas.
You know, the ultimate investment that would have been made in venture capital was really done over a long period of time.
It certainly wasn't funded all up front initially.
By a long shot, you know, they got a couple of people who were migrants who started out working in it initially.
You know, we started out making, you know,
and investment at a time in different various companies.
Part of the criteria would be to focus on companies that we tend to locate in Whitlam.
And ultimately, the Marty Center became the organization for Bruce Wither's Transmission Processing Division.
So, you know, it certainly wasn't a matter of putting $15 million in up front by a long shot.
Oh, no, I know that.
It was a gradual development over the period of several years.
But in comparison with Kingwood, for example, which, you know, people could raise an analogy, here's a corporate developed community, you know, and yet it's
on the surface and substantially, it's totally different.
Would there be a corporation, would the woodlands remain substantially the same if George Mitchell were, well, God forbid, if he should
pass away.
Well, eventually he will.
He'll leave.
He has to.
We all do.
But what will happen when that occurs?
Oh, you know, it's obviously, on any development, it's a product of, you know, the person that's in charge of it and the direction they want it to go.
You know, I would say at this point, you know, it would be hard to see.
I think the fundamental
you know, structure and organization is in place for the woodlands.
Obviously a different individual might do, would do different things, you know, some things differently than what George would do.
I think the basic concept of what's been developed to date would be hard to necessarily make any massive restructuring just simply because
So many of the streets and roads and buildings and other infrastructure is already in place, like Woodlands.
You know, the character of the buildings and companies that are already here can't change, you know, what the fundamental structure is.
And so, you know, it would just really depend on the mentality.

You know, Georgia's put a lot of infrastructure in, a lot of things, you know, some things have been done that other people might or might not conclude would be an essential part of the development, you know, so that would get to be a judgment call.
Would you essentially feel that things would march on pretty much as they have in the past because of the already built-in history or
Well, the infrastructure, Mr. President, is that a fair statement?
Yeah, I would think that's generally true.
Again, you can always dedicate, we've got about 4,000 net acres dedicated for commercial industrial space, you know, a lot of which has not been developed at this point.
You know, only the future will tell, for instance, if there will be a market for that
much space, you know, and so some of the character of that could change.
Some of the character of the undeveloped land could change, but I think the general approach to the development, you know, should pretty much be locked in, I would think.
Okay.
What are the challenges the woodlands faces presently, from your perspective, from a financial and operating perspective?
Well, obviously we've gone through in Houston since the early to mid 60s up to now.
It's been pretty tough times economically because of the downturn in the oil business, which affected the real estate business also.
So that's probably slowed the pace of development.
fair amount what otherwise would have been at today, simply because Houston had that negative growth during some of those years there.
You know, now we're being in the process, Houston is in the process of coming back from a business standpoint and a real estate standpoint, I think.
particularly in the residential area, there's still a big surplus of office space, commercial space in Houston.
And that's going to probably take a few more years to work through that system.
And so the residential here is going very strongly now in terms of numbers of people and families moving to the place.
And of course the overall concept really contemplates an integrated economic community of about 150,000 people ultimately.
We're around 30,000 now.
And that wouldn't be in the downtown.
We're somewhere, you know, at what we call the Metro Center.
You know, so in fact you sort of have really a city of 150,000 people with all the facilities and everything.

adjacent to it, with the concept that, you know, theoretically there'd be a job for every family that lives in the woodland, not that they'd all be matched up, but so that you'd have, so I think the big challenge would be to get, build up the commercial and other aspects of the operation that you'd float.
somewhat lagging behind the rest of the woodlands, primarily because of economic, or in large part, probably because of the economic conditions.
And there continues to be a national real estate flood, particularly in commercial space, so it's going to probably take some time to work through all that.
Again, the carrying cost on an investment like this is very large, and pace is an important part of the development.
The longer you carry it, the more the carrying costs are.
So it's going to be important to pick up pace there on the commercial side at some point.
Are you, or those who work with you or for you, what sort of staff reporting and analyses
are going to be needed to identify, for example, the rate or the pace of growth.
I know that goes on.
Well, obviously, that's an integral part of the planning process that the overall company goes through, not just for real estate.
But are there plans right now for dealing with the decade of the 90s, or with the next five years,
What are you forecasting, I guess is what I'm asking, in terms of ?
Oh, in terms of forecasting, I think generally speaking, they're probably looking at hopefully selling about 1,000 houses a year on average in the foreseeable future.
Hopefully the regional mall, as soon as the process has been worked on, hopefully that will get started here in the next year or two.
So it would just be a continuation that we need to fill up the existing office space in the woodlands and hopefully look for other commercial development opportunities.
The mall should be a good catalyst for development in the area.
things in that picture.
How does Mr. Mitchell utilize public relations to his advantage?
What's his operating philosophy in terms of the utilization of public relations?
Well, I was, you know, that's probably something he has spent a lot of time and, you know, is willing to devote some personal time to
to the public relations area, and I think probably uses it to his advantage and the company's advantage, you know, very well.
He's probably one of your more outspoken type of chief executive officers for a major company.
We probably have a more sophisticated operation in that respect than maybe other companies our size would tend to have.
And that's because of Mr. Mitchell?
Yeah, I would say primarily that's reflective of his wishes and desires, and I guess feeling that there's benefits to be gained from that time.
And I tend to agree that that's probably true.
So he does a good job of utilizing the media, I think.
He's generally known as an accessible type of person for the media.
So as a result, the public tends to get called on to comment and be a part of things that the otherwise wouldn't.
Generally speaking, most of the publicity that's generated tends to be in favor of the nation.
So any time you've got a particular real estate product or something to sell,
In all corporations, there's line responsibilities, and then there's the individuals fulfilling those line responsibilities frequently can be interchanged, or others can do that.
But then individuals also have unique, or not unique, but maybe special,
skills or abilities or capacities that they bring to a task.
I'm going to ask you to be modest.
What is it you bring?
What is George Mitchell, why does he want you around?
What's your real contribution to the corporation?
Well, obviously it's in the areas that I have, you know, primary responsibilities for.
Obviously I have an accounting degree, CPA.
I'd say my primary strengths are in the financial accounting financing area.
Aside from the overall administrative responsibilities, that's probably the major
major contribution that I make to the overall organization.
To be sure the company is well financed and the financial reporting is properly handled.
Since George is not inclined to sell a lot of equity in the company per se, most of our financing for the company's operations has to be
either internal cash flow, profits, or third party debt, or in some cases joint venture arrangements.
So that's obviously a company, a $2 billion company, and there are a lot of requirements in that area.
I don't want to take all your afternoon.
Are there questions I should have asked you that I didn't?
Oh, gosh, I'm sure there's a lot of things you could get into.
The, you know, I think, well, you know, Mitchell Energy, I guess, and Development Corp is, in a sense, two different businesses, you know, energy and real estate.
Obviously, when you have a 62% shareholder,
the chief executive president, chief executive officer, whatever else he wants to be in the company, you know, that's still to a large extent run as one company in the sense of overall direction.
So while the operations are distinct in and of themselves, you know, I still don't, you know,
financial standpoint and everything and sort of view it as an overall operation.

As I say, part of the thing that makes the real estate work, particularly during this development phase, is the strength of the energy operation in terms of the cash flows and the values and things of that nature.
debt on the real estate side tends to increase, you know, as projects and other things are developed.
You don't necessarily have the liquidity in a real estate operation that you have in an oil, gas, or energy operation.
And so it's important to, an important part of George being able to do what he's done on the real estate side and probably the presence of the energy operations there.

and apparent guarantees on the real estate debt, that while the values are there on the real estate side to support the debt, the liquidity, particularly when you have these downturns in the real estate economies, the real estate is not a liquid asset, even in good times.
In difficult times, it's impossible to move almost, unless it's up in a fire sale price.
The liquidity that the energy provides, or the fact that it's there to provide liquidity if it's needed, is an important part of how the real estate can be managed.
Yeah, that's come through.
Do you view the two corporations as essentially the same, as you were mentioning?
Well, it's the same in the sense that, as I say, they...
I mean, they do more than hold hands.
They...
I mean, the operating, I guess, my areas tend to be more of a common link between the two.
I mean, the people that operate the individual businesses are different.
Sure.
In real estate, transmission processing, production, things of that nature.
But in terms of the fact that, you know, the overall

resources of the company are utilized to achieve the overall operating results, you know, of the company, you know, to that extent that I was saying common, there's common ground there that makes part of it, you know, for instance, part of our major
financing for the company has been too public.
Mitchell Energy and Development Corp, the parent, has had two public debt issues at the parent company level, which basically has no operations.
It's just a holding company that owns the stock from the energy cell and the real estate cell.
So, a lot of your
probably better than half of our debt financing in the public debt markets and downstream to the two operations as needed to fund their operations.
Are you the architect of some of these debt management?
Well, it's my area, obviously, the financing is my responsibility.
So, to that extent, you know, it's all
We're financing as any Mitchell Energy and Development Corp, but not as an individual subsidiary.
Now, we do some of the financing, but it's a subsidiary level.
But a good part of it has been, you know, better than half of it probably has been at the Grand Country level, too.
Is there a flow both directions of
Well, that's maybe not what I wanted to ask.
The decision-making process, there's various cells or staff groups that do planning and development and what have you.
How are those decisions made?
The decisions of what you were just talking about, about how
You mentioned half is done at the parent company level and half is done elsewhere.
Who decides?
Well, it depends on what you're talking of in terms of financing aspects.
Most of that's part of my decision area.
In terms of the overall budget, each operating group prepares their capital budgets and their operating plans.
And we pull them all together on a company-wide basis.
And then to the extent you set priorities or there are limitations on resources, which there usually are, then George has to make the final decision.
So he sets the priorities in terms of?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, clearly.
Yeah, clearly.
OK. That's what I figured.
What else?
Oh, nothing just jumps out at me.
They say you could, on individual components, I'm sure we could talk on a lot of things, not knowing what level of detail you want to get into.
Well, part of the problem is I don't know that either.
Yeah.
Which is a bit of a challenge.
